'''Operation Falcon''' was an undercover operation conducted by the [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] (USFWS) and the [[Canadian Wildlife Service]] from 1982–1984. The investigation into the illegal sale of [[Endangered Species Act|federally protected birds]] resulted in 63 people being tried or taking a plea bargain. Of the cases that went to trial, there were 5 [[acquittal]]s, 5 [[felony]] convictions, 44 [[misdemeanor]] convictions and 1 [[lawsuit|civil]] conviction.<ref name="blade-saudi">{{cite news|date=November 17, 1984|newspaper=The Blade|location=Toledo|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XBMVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wQIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6912,7830805&dq=operation+falcon&hl=en|title=Canadian Says He Sold Rare Falcons to Saudi Royal Family|author=N.Y. Times News Service|page=23|publisher=Block Communications}}</ref> Jeff McPartlin, a [[Falconry|falconer]] who was reported to be integral to the operation, received the Monitor award for his work. He was later ejected from the [[North American Falconers Association]] because officials from the group felt "the man had deceived people".<ref name="ottawa-expel">{{cite news|title=Falconers' group expels undercover birdman|date=December 16, 1985|newspaper=The Citizen|location=Ottawa|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4qYyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=j-8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4375,3082236&dq=operation+falcon&hl=en|author=AP|page=C15|publisher=Canwest Global Communications Corporation}}</ref> Many falconers were upset at the tactics used during the investigation and felt that the sting inappropriately targeted bystanders rather than professional long term smugglers.<ref name="telegraph-agent">{{cite news|title=Falconer, alias secret agent, remains outcast|author=Ryckman, Lisa Levitt|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=Nashua|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5f8lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Q_wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6885,2216072&dq=operation+falcon&hl=en|page=12|date=May 8, 1987|publisher=Telegraph Publishing Company}}</ref> Additional information, much published by the National Falconry organization, is available in the following link: http://resourceclearinghouse.blogspot.com/2010/04/operation-falcon.html
